the world’s worst

natural disaster, Super Cyclone Pam, that occurred in March 2015. The consequences of such a catastrophe are still there and the country has not fully recovered. We have seen terrible destructions and misery. Many lives were lost and many more were uprooted from their homes and borders. 11 Municipalities were severely affected including Tafea Province, the Vanuatu’s main tourism area. But the resilience of the people of Vanuatu as a nation is exemplary. The hard work and impressive quick recovery from the cyclone by the local communities in the affected provinces benefited a lot from the support of development partners and even organizations that have never previously been associated with Vanuatu. But it is in the tourism industry where one can see the biggest growing development in our country. Right now tourism is the biggest income earner for Vanuatu and with the growing numbers in the economy and a large influx of our regional and international friends our resounding message is: “Ma belmak oh.” And I encourage you all to continue in our region to speak out our language which is only 30 more times away from Vanuatu popular pidgin called Bislama: “Noit dri moanemires”.
